problem_prompt: Approach the following question the way someone with a PhD in computer science would. Evaluate $\sqrt[3]{12}\times \sqrt[3]{20}\times \sqrt[3]{15}\times \sqrt[3]{60}$.
gpt_response:
To evaluate the expression $\sqrt[3]{12}\times \sqrt[3]{20}\times \sqrt[3]{15}\times \sqrt[3]{60}$, we can first simplify the individual cube roots by finding the prime factorization of each number:

$12 = 2^2 \times 3$
$20 = 2^2 \times 5$
$15 = 3 \times 5$
$60 = 2^2 \times 3 \times 5$

Next, we can simplify each cube root:

$\sqrt[3]{12} = 2\sqrt[3]{3}$
$\sqrt[3]{20} = 2\sqrt[3]{5}$
$\sqrt[3]{15} = \sqrt[3]{3}\sqrt[3]{5}$
$\sqrt[3]{60} = 2\sqrt[3]{3}\sqrt[3]{5}$

Finally, we can multiply the simplified expressions:

$2\sqrt[3]{3} \times 2\sqrt[3]{5} \times \sqrt[3]{3}\sqrt[3]{5} \times 2\sqrt[3]{3}\sqrt[3]{5}$
$= 4\sqrt[3]{3}\sqrt[3]{5} \times \sqrt[3]{3}\sqrt[3]{5} \times 2\sqrt[3]{3}\sqrt[3]{5}$
$= 8\sqrt[3]{3^2}\sqrt[3]{5^2}$
$= 8\sqrt[3]{9}\sqrt[3]{25}$
$= 8\cdot 3 \cdot 5$
$= 120$

Therefore, $\sqrt[3]{12}\times \sqrt[3]{20}\times \sqrt[3]{15}\times \sqrt[3]{60} = 120$.
